  "prompt": "What is the best fishing bait to use?",
  "response": "There's no single \"best\" fishing bait! The ideal bait depends on a bunch of factors. Here's a breakdown to help you choose the right one:\n\n**1. What are you trying to catch?**\n\n*   **Bass:** Worms, Crawfish, Minnows, Crankbaits, Jigs, Spinnerbaits, Topwater lures\n*   **Trout:** Worms, Salmon eggs, Corn, PowerBait, Flies, Small spinners\n*   **Catfish:** Chicken Liver, Nightcrawlers, Cut bait (fish), Stink bait, Hot dogs\n*   **Panfish (Bluegill, Crappie, Perch):** Worms, Crickets, Mealworms, Small minnows, Jigs, Small spinners\n*   **Walleye:** Minnows, Nightcrawlers, Leeches, Jigs, Crankbaits\n*   **Salmon:** Salmon eggs, Spoons, Spinners, Flies, Herring\n*   **Saltwater Fish (General):** Shrimp, Squid, Clams, Mussels, Cut bait (fish), Sand fleas\n\n**2. Where are you fishing?**\n\n*   **Freshwater:** Worms, Minnows, Insects, Artificial Lures (crankbaits, spinners, jigs)\n*   **Saltwater:** Shrimp, Squid, Cut bait, Live bait, Artificial Lures (spoons, jigs, swimbaits)\n\n**3. What time of year is it?**\n\n*   **Spring:** Fish are often more active and aggressive after the winter. Live bait and lures that mimic spawning prey can be effective.\n*   **Summer:** Fish may seek deeper, cooler water during the day. Adjust bait and lure presentations accordingly.\n*   **Fall:** Fish are often feeding heavily to prepare for winter. Larger baits and lures can be successful.\n*   **Winter:** Fish are often less active and may require slower presentations and smaller baits.\n\n**4. Water Clarity:**\n\n*   **Clear Water:** Natural-looking baits and lures in subtle colors often work best.\n*   **Murky Water:** Brighter colored baits and lures, or those that create vibration, can help fish find them.\n\n**5. Bait Types: Pros and Cons**\n\n*   **Live Bait:**\n    *   **Pros:** Very effective, natural presentation, attracts fish with scent and movement.\n    *   **Cons:** Can be expensive, requires proper storage, may be restricted in some areas.\n*   **Natural/Organic Bait (Worms, Corn, etc.):**\n    *   **Pros:** Relatively inexpensive, easy to use, readily available.\n    *   **Cons:** Can be messy, may not be as durable as other options.\n*   **Cut Bait:**\n        *   **Pros:** Great for catfish, cheap, effective if from fish that lives in that body of water\n        *   **Cons:** Messy, smelly, not as versatile\n*   **Artificial Lures:**\n    *   **Pros:** Reusable, durable, can be very effective when used correctly, wide variety of options.\n    *   **Cons:** Requires more skill to use effectively, can be expensive.\n*   **Prepared Bait (PowerBait, Stink Bait):**\n    *   **Pros:** Easy to use, long shelf life, can be very effective for certain species.\n    *   **Cons:** Can be messy, may not be as effective as live bait in all situations.\n\n**Tips for Choosing Bait:**\n\n*   **Ask local bait shops:** They will know what's working best in the area.\n*   **Observe what other anglers are using:** See what's catching fish.\n*   **Experiment:** Try different baits and lures until you find what works.\n*   **Check local regulations:** Make sure the bait you're using is legal in the area you're fishing.\n\nTo give you a more specific recommendation, I need more information.  **Tell me:**\n\n*   **What kind of fish are you trying to catch?**\n*   **Where are you fishing (lake, river, ocean, etc.)?**\n*   **What time of year is it?**\n*   **What's the water clarity like?**\n\nWith that information, I can give you much more tailored advice. Happy fishing!\n",
